<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="d653b8e9-99b0-5ab7-850d-ba12ac258de3" activityNameId="52bd6981-3ebd-4873-a009-39f4b8c01259" parentActivityId="25177fec-ecd4-5f03-a0a8-d2ecbb58da06" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">maize grain production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Zea mays L., corn</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">This activity starts with soil cultivation after the harvest of the previous crop.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This dataset includes cultivation of the field prior to planting, field treatments, planting, applications of nutrients and pesticides, and harvest. It ends with harvested maize grain at the farm gate, prior to storage.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of maize grain (fresh matter) in the US state of Iowa at farm, with a pre-drying moisture content of 19.4%. This dataset includes preparation of the field prior to planting, field treatments, planting, applications of nutrients and pesticides, and harvest. Residues are not collected but remain on the field post-harvest and overwinter.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The average yield of maize grain grown in Iowa for the 2014-2021 seasons was 12,138 kg/ha (wet mass) (USDA NASS (2021d).  The dataset reflects the average maize grain produced in Iowa from 2014 to 2021, inclusive, as that period allows for at least one value from USDA statistics for most parameters and generally three or more.  It reflects the mix of tillage practices (17% no till, 75% reduced till, 8% conventional tillage) (CTIC (2020a) and rotations (80% in rotation with soybean and 20% continuous corn) for maize grain. More than 90% of maize grown is genetically engineered, almost all stacking herbicide and insect tolerance traits. This dataset reflects practices consistent with that.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Area, productivity, use of mineral and organic fertilisers and pesticides, and irrigation inputs are based on farmer data reported to the U.S. Department of Agriculture. Lime use is based on soil pH and guidance from agricultural extension offices for maize grain. Field operations and equipment types and fuel use are based on materials provided to growers by the agricultural extension office(s), including farm budgets, and on survey information agricultural extension office(s) collect from growers, in conjunction with row spacing data from USDA.  Drainage (tile or ditch) is installed on 59.6% of crop land, based on state-level agricultural survey data from USDA.  Irrigation is included based on share of crop irrigated (less than 0.4% over the time period, USDA NASS (2018d)). Chemigation is included in this and is not treated as an additional operation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Area cultivated for maize grain in Iowa increased by 8% between 2000 and 2021 (USDA NASS data, 5 year rolling averages). US NRCS data indicates that total cropland in Iowa has expanded over the same period by 3% (NRCS 2020b). The expansion of cropland for all crops in Iowa in this period was supplied 100% from CRP (Conservation Research Program) land; thus, no direct conversion is included. Direct land use change is included in the dataset as calculated in the ecoinvent crop LCI tool. The total cropland change 1997 to 2017 was 3.0% for all crops in Iowa (NRCS 2020b).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Soil characteristics (pH, clay, SOM, slope) are based on the Iowa soil survey (ISPAID). No anti-erosion practices are assumed in the dataset; instead, the erosion soil loss reported in the U.S. Natural Resources Conservation Service's Natural Resource Inventory is used.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References: USDA NASS (2021d) Area, Production, Yield by State - Corn - 2010-2021. US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agricultural Statistics Service. https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov (direct query: https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov/results/331F88CC-004E-34D2-B825-F8F65DAC7879)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">CTIC (2020a) OpTIS - Operational Tillage Information System. Conservation Technology Information Center (CTIC). https://www.ctic.org/optis_tabular_queryaccessed March 23, 2021</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">USDA NASS (2018d) 2018 Irrigation and Water Management Survey (2017 Census of Agriculture). US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.nass.usda.gov/Publications/AgCensus/2017/Online_Resources/Farm_and_Ranch_Irrigation_Survey/index.php</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">USDA NASS (2021j) Corn, Grain, Irrigated - Acres Harvested 2000-2021; Corn, Grain, Non-Irrigated - Acres Harvested 2000-2018. US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Iowa Soil Survey &amp; Digital Soil Data: ISPAID. Version 8.1.1 (2017). https://www.extension.iastate.edu/soils/ispaid</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">NRCS (2020b)  Land Cover/use of non-Federal rural land, by State and year, in the 2017 National Resources Inventory. USDA, Natural Resources Conservation Service. http://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/NRCS_RCA/reports/nri_crop_nat.html, https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/portal/nrcs/rca/national/technical/nra/rca/text/#NRI%20Cropland</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="e2e1f67d-3393-4182-86f6-1ada2f77c3e5">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">0111:Growing of cereals (except rice), leguminous crops and oil seeds</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="d38650a8-8c23-4941-9292-f9d7a4dce29b">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">US-IA</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Production of maize grain in Iowa (US-IA).</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset reflects current practice for maize grain in Iowa as of 2022.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2014-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The valid period covers 2014-01-01 through 2021-12-31 based on primary data sources. The production volumes, areas and applications are covered by data throughout the time period (annual for production and area, alternate years for applications). Due to disruption in 2020, some USDA data was reported for 2021 instead. Because the specific pesticides used show time-dependent trends, the most recent 3 years of data are used to avoid underweighting the most dominant pesticides currently used and to avoid skewing impacts based on compounds no longer in use. Field operations are based on current enterprise crop budgets and change little year to year.  Data for manure applications were only available for time periods prior to the valid period but represent the best available option.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
