      <intermediateExchange id="1a461120-de9a-5392-805d-73278e8008d1" unitId="86bbe475-8a8f-44d8-914c-e398787e7121" amount="0.000101667480047858" intermediateExchangeId="75168394-3da2-467a-90a1-285836ccd00d" activityLinkId="ce3b617c-7d3c-5df2-9a64-0e9554f11941">
        <name xml:lang="en">fertilising, by broadcaster</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">ha</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">1.234 ha/ha (1.02E-4 ha/kg maize grain) fertilising, by broadcaster
Average application rates for mineral fertilisers (NPKS) on maize grain in Iowa are: 1.70 N applications on 96.5% of cropped area, 1.05 P applications on 68.5% of cropped area, 1.08 K applications on 67.8% of cropped area, and 1.05 S applications on 17.3% of cropped area (USDA NASS 2021f, NPKS data from 2014, 2016, 2018, 2021). Applications of N are split between anhydrous ammonia and other NPK(S) fertilsers because they are generally applied differently, with different equipment. Other than anhydrous ammonia, most NPK(S) fertilisers are applied together via broadcast application.
Anhydrous ammonia application (knifing/injection) is calculated as market share of N that is anhydrous ammonia * total N applications (=0.42). Other N application is then: total USDA N applications less applications of anhydrous ammonia (=1.28). The market share of N that is anhydrous ammonia is calculated from fertiliser market group shares crossed with meeting NPKS nutrient demand (here, 24.78%). Thus, the dataset includes 0.41 anhydrous ammonia applications via injection (0.42 * 96.5% of crop area with applied N) and 1.23 other N applications via broadcast (1.28 * 96.5%). Since the number of passes for N application after removing the anhydrous ammonia share is greater than the maximum number of passes reported for the other nutrients, this dataset assumes that any other fertiliser applications are reflected under that pass and the total fertiliser broadcast fertiliser passes are thus 1.23.

Field operations are as identified in crop- and rotation-specific enterprise crop budgets supplied by the regional agricultural extension office and matched to equipment type in the budget or crop guidance.  (ISU Extension 2021a, ISU Extension 2021b, ISU Extension 2021c, ISU Extension 2021d, ISU Extension 2021e, ISU Extension 2021f; Plastina A and Johanns A 2021, Hanna, Mark 2005).  Operations are matched to equipment type and where multiple options are available, the share of each is determined from guidance and annual farmer survey data (Custom Rate Summaries) for contracted operations/equipment. Where an operation applies only to a portion of the harvested area, the number of passes has been scaled by the % of harvested area to which it applies (e.g., manure spreading or insecticide) as indicated by USDA statistics (applications) or USDA reports (manure use) or as otherwise indicated in enterprise crop budgets.
Source(s): 
USDA NASS (2021f) CORN - APPLICATIONS, MEASURED IN LB / ACRE / YEAR, AVG and NUMBER / YEAR (fertilizer and pesticides, amount, number of applications) - 2000-2021. US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agricultural Statistics Service. https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov (direct query: https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov/results/5BCE1263-5F91-31A9-B3DE-117AFBDDFF20); ISU Extension (2021a) Crop Production Costs Budgets - tabulated. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/pdf/a1-20.pdf; ISU Extension (2021b) Crop Production Costs Budget - Corn following Corn. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/xls/a1-20cfc_tbl1.xlsx; ISU Extension (2021c) Crop Production Costs Budget - Corn following Soybeans. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/xls/a1-20cfs_tbl2.xlsx; ISU Extension (2021d) Crop Production Costs Budget - Low-till corn following Soybeans. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/xls/a1-20lowtillcfstbl6.xlsx; ISU Extension (2021e) Crop Production Costs Budget - Strip-till corn following Soybeans. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/xls/a1-20striptillcfstbl5.xlsx; ISU Extension (2021f) Budgets and other resources from IA Extension. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/cdcostsreturns.html; Plastina A and Johanns A (2021) Iowa Farm Custom Rate Survey, 2021 (2018, 2019, 2020). Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/pdf/a3-10.pdf; Hanna, Mark (2005) Fuel Required for Field Operations. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/pdf/a3-24.pdf</comment>
