      <intermediateExchange id="cccb6f15-a908-59fb-bab5-e82aba019547" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="001317-65-3" amount="0.00522643652569148" intermediateExchangeId="64cea105-f89a-4f95-ae44-84ff904a28fc" activityLinkId="2659aacd-df83-5c93-9180-56a0c05ff487">
        <name xml:lang="en">limestone, crushed, washed</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Application of limestone to raise soil pH, 63.44 kg/ha (5.23E-3 kg/kg maize grain), calculated as (mass of lime applied to treated acres (2 t/treated ha)) * fraction of crop area treated with lime (6.42%, from soil grid level soil pH values (ISPAID8.1.1; USDA NASS) / (5  years between applications, based on Mallarino A P, Pagani A, Sawyer J E 2011). 
Lime is applied to all soils with pH below 6, and to high subsoil pH soils with pH between 6.5 and 6, based on expert guidance (J.E. Sawyer 2020). Cropped area needing liming is determined from grid level (sub-county level) data for soil pH and formation type (ISPAID8.1.1), weighted with county-level production data (NASS). The increase in pH with lime application remains dominant through at least 4 years from application (Mallarino A P, Pagani A, Sawyer J E 2011).
Sources: 
Iowa Soil Survey &amp; Digital Soil Data: ISPAID. Version 8.1.1 (2017). https://www.extension.iastate.edu/soils/ispaid; Sawyer, J.E (2020) Presentation "Soil pH and Liming". Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology.  http://www.agronext.iastate.edu/soilfertility/info/SoilpHandLiming2020.pdfaccessed October 1, 2021; Mallarino A P, Pagani A, Sawyer J E (2011) Corn and soybean response to soil pH level and liming. Paper presented at the 2011 Integrated Crop Management Conference. Iowa State University.Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/128983337.pdfaccessed November 17, 2021</comment>
