      <intermediateExchange id="432e40c4-782b-5380-91df-8cc2822c11cd" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" amount="0.00190923131823985" intermediateExchangeId="cff23b42-5fa8-471b-b6fb-8a2cca249ca8" activityLinkId="1c608e58-eca0-5d8f-9e7a-424184718473">
        <name xml:lang="en">maize seed, for sowing</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Each planted hectare uses 23.17 kg seed (1.91E-3 kg/kg maize grain). This value is calculated from a seeding rate of 86,487 seeds/ha (Licht M, Parvej M R, Baum M 2019, Licht M 2020) and an average seed count of 3,732 seeds/kg (averaged from Licht M and Clemens Z 2020, Leinfelder-Miles M 2018). More than 90% of planted maize corn is genetically engineered (state by state variation 0.3-1.8%), mostly with stacked herbicide-tolerant and insect-tolerant traits (USDA NASS 2022). The dataset uses the less variable agronomically optimal seeding rate rather than the more variable, though potentially lower, economically optimal rate. Germination and stand losses are accounted for in the seeding rate. The uncertainty parameters are calculated from the uncertainty on the yield and the  year on year variation on the order of 6-17% found in analysis of USDA NASS data for 2014-2016 (Mekonnen et al 2018).  
Sources:
Licht M, Parvej M R, Baum M (2019) Guide to Iowa Corn Planting. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://store.extension.iastate.edu/product/5475, Licht M (2020) "Updated views on corn and soybean planting recommendations" 4/1/20 10:43. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://crops.extension.iastate.edu/blog/mark-licht/updated-views-corn-and-soybean-planting-recommendations, USDA NASS. (2020). Crops/Stocks Survey (or Agricultural Survey) for the years 2000-20 - Recent Trends in GE Adoption. US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/adoption-of-genetically-engineered-crops-in-the-us/documentation/ , Mekonnen et al (2018) Water, Energy, and Carbon Footprints of Bioethanol from the U.S. and Brazil. Environ. Sci. Technol. 52:14508–14518. Mesfin M. Mekonnen, Thiago L. Romanelli, Chittaranjan Ray, Arjen Y. Hoekstra, Adam J. Liska, and Christopher M.U. Neale. https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.est.8b03359</comment>
