      <elementaryExchange id="a59804ca-0573-5c4e-a11f-9b89b70294ac" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="007723-14-0" amount="2.87438052143934E-06" elementaryExchangeId="b2631209-8374-431e-b7d5-56c96c6b6d79" formula="P">
        <name xml:lang="en">Phosphorus</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Phosphorus emissions to surface water are based on the SALCA-P model (Prasuhn 2006), but using state-specific data for agricultural land (not crop-specific). The erosion and soil test values encompass the state-wide reported cropped area of maize grain in Iowa for all tillage practices (OPTiS 2020) and across all rotation patterns (Socolar et al 2021).Soil Phosphorus losses are calculated from an annual soil loss from water erosion on agricultural soils in Iowa of 12.89t/ha/year (NRCS 2020a)with a Phosphorus soil concentration of 20mg/kg soil, the median value from 1,139,873 soil test samples reported for Iowa in the 2020 Soil Test Survey, (the average of the 2005, 2010, 2015, and 2020 median soil Phosphorus concentrations is 24.mg/kg soil) (Bruulsema T and Jones J D 2021).No enrichment factor has been applied, because the phosphorus soil concentration samples are specifically agricultural land in the study area and thus any enrichment as a result of synthetic and organic fertilisers is already caputred in the soil test.An active cultivation duration of 6.8 months (0.56 year), covering cultivation through harvest (from weekly progress reports,USDA NASS 2021e), is used to adjust the annual erosion to the crop share (see Faist-Emmenegger et al 2009).No adjustment has been made for the presence of drainage (installed on 64.9% of crop land, USDA 2018) or any anti-erosion practices.Sources: 
NRCS (2020a) Soil losses from erosion (water and wind) on cultivated cropland, in the 2017 National Resources Inventory. USDA, Natural Resources Conservation Service. http://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/NRCS_RCA/reports/nri_crop_nat.html
Bruulsema T and Jones J D (2021) Soil Test Summary 2020. Foundation for Agronomic Research and Plant Nutrition Canada present this 2020 summary of soil test levels in North America. Foundation for Agronomic Research, Plant Nutrition Canada. https://soiltest.tfi.org/about/about_soil_test_summaryaccessed August 30, 2021
USDA NASS (2021e) CORN - PROGRESS (planted, emerged, harvested) - 2000-2021. US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agricultural Statistics Service. https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov (direct query: https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov/results/C4906A1B-9BAA-31C4-8033-B8D950FECC3E)
USDA (2018) 2017 Census of Agriculture, Volume 1, Chapter 2: State Level Data - Table 41.  Land Use Practices:  2017 and 2012 (live table: https://www.nass.usda.gov/Quick_Stats/CDQT/chapter/2/table/41/state/US). US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.nass.usda.gov/Publications/AgCensus/2017/Full_Report/Volume_1,_Chapter_2_US_State_Level/st99_2_0041_0041.pdf
Prasuhn, V (2006) Erfassung der PO4-Austräge für die Ökobilanzierung. SALCA-Phosphor. Zü-rich, CH, Agrocope FAL Reckenholz. Agrocope.  
Faist Emmenegger M, Reinhard J, Zah R (2009) Sustainability Quick Check for Biofuels - in- termediate background report. With contributions from T. Ziep, R. Weichbrodt, Prof. Dr. V. Wohlgemuth, FHTW Berlin and A. Roches, R. Freiermuth Knuchel, Dr. G. Gaillard, Agroscope Reckenholz-Tänikon. Dübendorf. . https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Rainer-Zah/publication/230725635_SQCB_-_Sustainability_Quick_Check_for_Biofuels_Second_draft_18th_February_2009_-_Intermediate_Background_Report_With_contributions_from_T_Ziep_R_Weichbrodt_Prof_Dr_V_Wohlgemuth_FHTW_Berlin_and_A_Roche/links/56b458fb08ae1f8aa45392e6/SQCB-Sustainability-Quick-Check-for-Biofuels-Second-draft-18th-February-2009-Intermediate-Background-Report-With-contributions-from-T-Ziep-R-Weichbrodt-Prof-Dr-V-Wohlgemuth-FHTW-Berlin-and-A-R.pdf</comment>
